===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{lb|en|astronomy}} The point in the sky [[vertically]] above a given position or observer; the [[point]] in the [[celestial sphere]] opposite the [[nadir]].
#: {{ant|en|nadir|perigee}}
#* '''1638''' Herbert, Sir Thomas ''Some years travels into divers parts of Asia and Afrique''
#*: {{quote|en|The 12 day wee had the wind high and large ſo that in two dayes ſaile we made the Sunne our '''Zenith''' or verticall point{{...}}}}
#* '''1671–1693''': Rev. Thomas Jolly, ''private notebook''; printed in: '''1895''', Henry Fishwick (editor), ''The Note Book of the Rev. Thomas Jolly: A.D. 1671–1693. Extracts from the Church Books of Altham and Wymondhouses, 1649–1725. And an Account of the Jolly Family of Standish, Gorton, and Altham'', [http://books.google.co.uk/books?ei=L-9bSa-FKYuiyAS3xqmCDA&id=TA71Bp2xMq0C&dq=%22of+christ+and+his+gospell%2C%22&q=zenith&pgis=1#search_anchor page 44]
#*: {{quote|en|In this 10th m. appeared that prodigious Comett the tayl whereof was like the blade of a double edged sword, and reached almost from the horizon to the '''zenith'''.}}
#* '''1938''', [[w:Xavier Herbert|Xavier Herbert]], ''[[w:Capricornia (novel)|Capricornia]]'', New York: D. Appleton-Century, 1943, Chapter XI, p. 180, [https://archive.org/details/capricornianovel00herb]
#*: {{quote|en|In the east a pillar of cloud reared from horizon to '''zenith''', with a kind of arm outstretched like a threatening colossus.}}
# {{lb|en|astronomy}} The [[highest]] point in the sky reached by a [[celestial body]].
#* '''1719-''' [[w:Daniel Defoe|Daniel Defoe]], ''[[w:Robinson Crusoe|Robinson Crusoe]]''
#*: {{quote|en|{{...}} in the middle of the day, when the sun was in the '''zenith''', the violence of the heat was too great to stir out {{...}}}}
#* '''1920''', [[w:Peter B. Kyne|Peter B. Kyne]], ''The Understanding Heart'', Chapter II:
#*: {{quote|en|As far to the west as Monica could see, her world was a sea of fog, {{...}}. Above it arched a cerulean sky; as the sun climbed to the '''zenith''', {{...}}, the fog gradually took on a bluish tinge.}}
# {{lb|en|by extension}} Highest point or [[state]]; [[peak]].
#: {{ux|en|Winning the continental championship was the '''zenith''' of my career.}}
#: {{syn|en|acme|apogee|culmination|pinnacle}}
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Tempest|I|ii|passage=I find my '''zenith''' doth depend upon / A most auspicious star.}}
#* {{RQ:Macaulay History of England|chapter=13|passage=It was during those civil troubles {{...}} this aspiring family reached the '''zenith'''.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|page=173|year=1900|author=William Beckford| title=The History of the Caliph Vathek| url=http://books.google.com/books?id=KnArAAAAMAAJ| passage="There for a while I enjoyed myself in the '''zenith''' of glory and pleasure."}}

